# gen103 (L16) — the bilingual ratchet (LOOP.md). Italian uses the subject-first
# interrogative "<x> è un <y>?"; a trailing '?' marks the query through the SAME
# core path as English (no duplicated logic — the fix was in the parser, not a
# second phrasebook). So re-derivation + consequence announcement fire in Italian.

> ogni uomo è un mortale
< Learned rule: mortale(X) :- uomo(X).
> socrates è un uomo
< Learned: uomo(socrates).
# Subject-first interrogative is a QUERY, not an assertion, thanks to the '?'.
> socrates è un mortale?
< Yes.
# The correction re-derives the conclusion and volunteers the consequence.
> socrates non è un uomo
< Learned: not uomo(socrates). Then socrates is no longer a mortale.